### Emergency Value Stream Network

![[Emergency Department Domain Value Stream Network.png]]

This Emergency Domain [[Value Stream Network]] answers a question every hospital executive eventually asks: _"What actually happens when someone shows up at our Emergency Department, and who else gets pulled into the mission?"_

The Emergency Department sits at the centre of a complex web of value delivery. Unlike back-office functions that can often operate in relative isolation, emergency care is an orchestration challenge — triggering value streams across nearly every domain in the hospital organization, plus partners outside your walls.
### The Core Value Stream

The Emergency Department Value Stream flows through five stages that any ED clinician would recognize: **Present → Triage → Assess → Treat → Transfer or Discharge**. Each stage incrementally delivers value to the patient, from initial arrival through final disposition. The model correctly contains these stages within the Emergency Department domain, showing that this is where ownership and accountability live.

But here's where it gets interesting. Those dashed "Triggers" and "Flows to" relationships radiating outward tell the real story of emergency medicine: you can't do it alone.
### The Value Stream Network Effect

The model shows how Emergency Domain activity cascades across organizational boundaries:

- **External Partners** — Emergency Medical Services operates outside the Hospital Organization entirely (note the compositional boundary), yet their EMS Value Stream triggers the entire emergency care journey. This is your extended enterprise in action — a partner whose value stream feeds directly into yours.
- **Clinical Support Services** — The Triage, Assess, and Treat stages don't just process patients in isolation. They trigger and flow information to Laboratory, Inpatient Imaging, Pharmacy, and Housekeeping value streams. These are the behind-the-scenes operations that determine whether your ED runs smoothly or grinds to a halt waiting for results, medications, or clean beds.
- **Corporate Services** — Every patient presenting can trigger the Shift Scheduling Value Stream (if you need you need staff coverage), while Transfer or Discharge triggers Patient Billing. The Supply Management Value Stream runs in support of it all. These aren't glamorous, but try running an ED without them.
- **Inpatient Domain** — When patients can't go home, the Transfer or Discharge stage triggers Critical Care, Surgery, or the general Inpatient Value Stream. The Porter Value Stream — which connects to several of these destinations — handles the physical movement of patients through the organization.
- **Primary Care** — That "Informs" relationship to Primary Care is subtle but important. This represents the continuity of care loop — ensuring the patient's regular provider knows what happened in your ED.

### Why This Model Matters

This isn't just a pretty picture. This Domain View enables several critical conversations:

- **Capacity Planning** — When ED volumes spike, which downstream value streams become bottlenecks? The model shows you exactly where to look.
- **Investment Decisions** — If you're considering ED expansion, this model immediately reveals the ripple effects across Laboratory, Imaging, Pharmacy, and every other connected domain.
- **Accountability Mapping** — When the Transfer or Discharge stage takes too long, is it an ED problem or an Inpatient beds problem? The model clarifies ownership boundaries.
- **Integration Architecture** — For your technology team, this view becomes the roadmap for application integration. Every "Triggers" relationship likely implies data exchange requirements.
### The Stealth EA Principles at Work

This model embodies the core [[Stealth EA Metamodel]] concepts: Value Stream Stages contained within their owning Domain, Domains organized within the larger Hospital Organization, and explicit trigger/flow relationships showing how value streams interconnect across boundaries. It demonstrates that capabilities without value streams are ingredients without recipes — here we see the recipe for emergency care in action.

Most importantly, [[Stealth EA/Blog Entries/The power of a one page model|it fits on one page]]. An executive can grasp the complexity without needing a decoder ring, while the clinical operations team can see exactly how their world connects to everyone else's.
